## Critical Rules

### DO:
✅ Use @StateObject when view creates the observable object
✅ Use @ObservedObject when object is passed from parent
✅ Mark @State properties as private
✅ Break complex views into smaller components
✅ Use .task for async operations tied to view lifecycle
✅ Add accessibility labels to all meaningful UI elements
✅ Support Dynamic Type
✅ Use LazyVStack/LazyHStack for large lists
✅ Include comprehensive preview providers
✅ Use @MainActor for UI updates
✅ Leverage @ViewBuilder for flexible layouts
✅ Test with VoiceOver and accessibility inspector

### DON'T:
❌ Use @ObservedObject when view creates the object (causes recreation)
❌ Mutate @State directly from outside the view
❌ Create massive monolithic views
❌ Forget to handle loading and error states
❌ Use .onAppear for critical data loading (use .task)
❌ Hardcode colors (use semantic colors)
❌ Ignore Dynamic Type scaling
❌ Put business logic in views
❌ Forget cancellation for async tasks
❌ Use VStack for large collections (causes performance issues)
❌ Skip accessibility testing
❌ Nest too many view hierarchies (affects performance)

## Component Creation Checklist

When creating a SwiftUI view, ensure:

- [ ] View is focused on single responsibility
- [ ] State management uses appropriate property wrappers
- [ ] Accessibility labels and hints added
- [ ] Dynamic Type support verified
- [ ] Loading states handled
- [ ] Error states handled
- [ ] Empty states handled
- [ ] Async operations use .task or proper cancellation
- [ ] Preview providers included with multiple configurations
- [ ] Performance optimized (LazyStacks where needed)
- [ ] Animations are smooth and meaningful
- [ ] View conforms to Apple's HIG
- [ ] Dark mode tested
- [ ] Different device sizes tested
- [ ] VoiceOver tested

## Common Pitfalls and Solutions

### Pitfall 1: @ObservedObject Recreation
```swift
// ❌ BAD: Object recreated on every view update
struct ContentView: View {
    @ObservedObject var viewModel = ViewModel()
    // viewModel gets recreated!
}

// ✅ GOOD: Use @StateObject for ownership
struct ContentView: View {
    @StateObject private var viewModel = ViewModel()
    // viewModel persists across updates
}
```

### Pitfall 2: Forgetting @MainActor
```swift
// ❌ BAD: UI update off main thread
class ViewModel: ObservableObject {
    @Published var data: [Item] = []

    func loadData() async {
        data = try await fetchData()
        // Crashes or warnings!
    }
}

// ✅ GOOD: Ensure main actor
@MainActor
class ViewModel: ObservableObject {
    @Published var data: [Item] = []

    func loadData() async {
        data = try await fetchData()
        // Safe!
    }
}
```

### Pitfall 3: Task Lifecycle
```swift
// ❌ BAD: Task doesn't cancel
struct DataView: View {
    @State private var data: [Item] = []

    var body: some View {
        Text("Data")
            .onAppear {
                Task {
                    data = try await fetchData()
                    // Continues even if view disappears
                }
            }
    }
}

// ✅ GOOD: Auto-cancellation with .task
struct DataView: View {
    @State private var data: [Item] = []

    var body: some View {
        Text("Data")
            .task {
                data = try await fetchData()
                // Automatically cancelled when view disappears
            }
    }
}
```

## Examples

### Complete Example: User Profile Card

```swift
import SwiftUI

// MARK: - Model
struct User: Identifiable, Equatable {
    let id: UUID
    let name: String
    let email: String
    let avatarURL: URL?
    let isOnline: Bool

    static let sample = User(
        id: UUID(),
        name: "John Doe",
        email: "john@example.com",
        avatarURL: nil,
        isOnline: true
    )
}

// MARK: - Main View
struct UserProfileCard: View {
    let user: User
    let onTap: () -> Void

    var body: some View {
        Button(action: onTap) {
            HStack(spacing: 16) {
                AvatarView(url: user.avatarURL, isOnline: user.isOnline)

                VStack(alignment: .leading, spacing: 4) {
                    Text(user.name)
                        .font(.headline)
                        .foregroundColor(.primary)

                    Text(user.email)
                        .font(.subheadline)
                        .foregroundColor(.secondary)
                }

                Spacer()

                Image(systemName: "chevron.right")
                    .foregroundColor(.secondary)
                    .accessibilityHidden(true)
            }
            .padding()
        }
        .buttonStyle(.plain)
        .background(Color(.systemBackground))
        .cornerRadius(12)
        .shadow(color: .black.opacity(0.1), radius: 4, y: 2)
        .accessibilityElement(children: .combine)
        .accessibilityLabel("\(user.name), \(user.email)")
        .accessibilityHint("Tap to view profile details")
        .accessibilityAddTraits(.isButton)
    }
}

// MARK: - Avatar View
private struct AvatarView: View {
    let url: URL?
    let isOnline: Bool

    var body: some View {
        ZStack(alignment: .bottomTrailing) {
            AsyncImage(url: url) { image in
                image
                    .resizable()
                    .aspectRatio(contentMode: .fill)
            } placeholder: {
                Image(systemName: "person.circle.fill")
                    .resizable()
                    .foregroundColor(.secondary)
            }
            .frame(width: 60, height: 60)
            .clipShape(Circle())

            if isOnline {
                Circle()
                    .fill(Color.green)
                    .frame(width: 16, height: 16)
                    .overlay(
                        Circle()
                            .stroke(Color(.systemBackground), lineWidth: 2)
                    )
            }
        }
        .accessibilityLabel(isOnline ? "Online" : "Offline")
    }
}

// MARK: - Preview
#Preview("Default") {
    UserProfileCard(user: .sample) {
        print("Tapped")
    }
    .padding()
}

#Preview("Dark Mode") {
    UserProfileCard(user: .sample) {
        print("Tapped")
    }
    .padding()
    .preferredColorScheme(.dark)
}

#Preview("Large Text") {
    UserProfileCard(user: .sample) {
        print("Tapped")
    }
    .padding()
    .environment(\.dynamicTypeSize, .xxxLarge)
}
```

### Example: Data-Driven List with MVVM

```swift
// MARK: - Model
struct Article: Identifiable {
    let id: UUID
    let title: String
    let excerpt: String
    let date: Date
}

// MARK: - ViewModel
@MainActor
class ArticlesViewModel: ObservableObject {
    @Published var articles: [Article] = []
    @Published var isLoading = false
    @Published var errorMessage: String?

    func loadArticles() async {
        isLoading = true
        errorMessage = nil

        do {
            // Simulate API call
            try await Task.sleep(for: .seconds(1))
            articles = mockArticles()
            isLoading = false
        } catch {
            errorMessage = error.localizedDescription
            isLoading = false
        }
    }

    private func mockArticles() -> [Article] {
        (1...20).map { i in
            Article(
                id: UUID(),
                title: "Article \(i)",
                excerpt: "This is a preview of article \(i)",
                date: Date()
            )
        }
    }
}

// MARK: - View
struct ArticlesListView: View {
    @StateObject private var viewModel = ArticlesViewModel()

    var body: some View {
        NavigationStack {
            Group {
                if viewModel.isLoading {
                    ProgressView()
                } else if let error = viewModel.errorMessage {
                    ErrorView(error: error) {
                        Task { await viewModel.loadArticles() }
                    }
                } else if viewModel.articles.isEmpty {
                    EmptyStateView()
                } else {
                    ArticlesList(articles: viewModel.articles)
                }
            }
            .navigationTitle("Articles")
            .task {
                await viewModel.loadArticles()
            }
            .refreshable {
                await viewModel.loadArticles()
            }
        }
    }
}

// MARK: - Articles List
private struct ArticlesList: View {
    let articles: [Article]

    var body: some View {
        List(articles) { article in
            ArticleRow(article: article)
        }
    }
}

// MARK: - Article Row
private struct ArticleRow: View {
    let article: Article

    var body: some View {
        VStack(alignment: .leading, spacing: 8) {
            Text(article.title)
                .font(.headline)

            Text(article.excerpt)
                .font(.subheadline)
                .foregroundColor(.secondary)
                .lineLimit(2)

            Text(article.date, style: .date)
                .font(.caption)
                .foregroundColor(.secondary)
        }
        .padding(.vertical, 4)
    }
}

// MARK: - Supporting Views
private struct ErrorView: View {
    let error: String
    let retry: () -> Void

    var body: some View {
        VStack(spacing: 16) {
            Image(systemName: "exclamationmark.triangle")
                .font(.largeTitle)
                .foregroundColor(.orange)
            Text(error)
                .multilineTextAlignment(.center)
            Button("Retry", action: retry)
                .buttonStyle(.borderedProminent)
        }
        .padding()
    }
}

private struct EmptyStateView: View {
    var body: some View {
        VStack(spacing: 16) {
            Image(systemName: "doc.text")
                .font(.largeTitle)
                .foregroundColor(.secondary)
            Text("No articles yet")
                .font(.headline)
        }
    }
}
```

## Conclusion

Following these guidelines will help you create SwiftUI views that are:
- **Well-structured** with proper composition and separation of concerns
- **Performant** with appropriate use of lazy loading and state management
- **Accessible** with full VoiceOver and Dynamic Type support
- **Maintainable** with clear MVVM architecture
- **Type-safe** with proper Swift types and protocols
- **Production-ready** with comprehensive error and loading states

Remember: SwiftUI is declarative - describe what you want, not how to do it. Start simple, let SwiftUI handle the details, and add complexity only when needed. Always test with accessibility features enabled and different device configurations.

